Maty Fall Diba was born in Senegal on May 1, 2001 where she lived in Ouest Foire, just outside Dakar, with her mother and siblings until the age of 9, when she arrived to Chiampo, Vicenza, to join her father, who had come to Italy 27 years ago. Maty is in the fourth year of high school and last May became an Italian citizen as well as turning 18. Last September Maty was chosen by #PierpaoloPiccioli to close the #Valentino SS20 show and walked for the house once again during the Couture week in January.

#ProtectVenice

Our February issue marks the second half of our creative effort commitment in helping Venice, following the severe damage caused by recent flooding. By using only illustrations in our January issue, we contributed, with the money saved on production, to the restoration of Fondazione Querini Stampalia. Now, with our February issue, we give the most precious and visible asset that a magazine has to offer - its cover - to ask our readers to help and donate to the current account that the city of Venice has opened to support not only churches and museums, but also those people whose houses and shops have been affected.
Built when the world was still on a human scale, Venice represents Italy, as they both face the challenge of protecting their past in order to be able to shape their future.
â€”-

*NO PHOTOSHOOT PRODUCTION WAS REQUIRED IN THE MAKING OF THIS ISSUE
A preview of the January 2020 Vogue Italia Special Issue on newsstands January 7th
@Paolo.Ventura featuring @FeliceNova in @Gucci
Cover 7 of 7
***
"All of the covers, as well as the features of our January issue, have been drawn by artists, ranging from well-known art icons and emerging talents to comic book legends, who have created without travelling, shipping entire wardrobes of clothes or polluting in any way. The challenge was to prove it is possible to show clothes without photographing them. This is a first, Vogue Italia has never had an illustrated cover: and as far as I know no issue of Vogue in which photography is not the primary visual medium has ever been printed.
Thanks to this idea, and to these artists' process, the money saved in the production of this issue will go towards financing a project that really deserves it: the restoration of Fondazione Querini Stampalia in Venice, severely damaged by the recent floods.â€ @efarneti

The artist who collaborated with Hugo Pratt, Federico Fellini, and Alejandro Jodorowsky, this year, is celebrating fifty years of career. â€œFor my cover I referenced the greatest of models, Michelangeloâ€™s David, but in female form. I wanted to recreate the same pose, the quiet pride of the victor, which is the attitude that represents femininity in our times despite male resistance.  David took on Goliathâ€™s brute force with a slingshot. He won by using intelligence. Today, women have a great Goliath to defeat: male chauvinism, the patriarchy, and violence.â€ #MiloManara

The challenge was to prove it is possible to show clothes without photographing them. This is a first, Vogue Italia has never had an illustrated cover: and as far as I know no issue of Vogue in which photography is not the primary visual medium has ever been printed.
Thanks to this idea, and to these artists' process, the money saved in the production of this issue will go towards financing a project that really deserves it: the restoration of Fondazione Querini Stampalia in Venice, severely damaged by the recent floods". @efarneti

Today we announce the launch of #VogueValues , a set of guiding principles that every Vogue editors-in-chief across the world has collaborated on. "Vogue Italia has in its DNA the ability to capture, and sometimes even drive, the major transformations occurring in our society," stated the Editor-in-chief of Vogue Italia, Emanuele Farneti. â€œA good example is the 2008 Black Issue, the first to bring the topic of diversity in fashion under the spotlight. Today, as on that occasion, our mission is to uphold the values in which we believe and which we continue to eagerly champion alongside our colleagues across the world. The January issue will be a manifesto of such values, developed around the one that encompasses them all: creativity. Because today, more than ever before, we truly believe that beauty can save the world."
Watch to read the full statement, and let us know what you think in the comments below.
